&#61607;    Include domain, technical, and functional experts in your resource management plan.</p>',1501497497,NULL,1,0),(42,39,19,14,'We all agree quality assurance (QA) and testing is critical, and we have stories of moments which proved this right!  Let me share one from early in my career. I was part of an end-to-end testing team of a mission critical project – a new, omni-channel product launch for a financial services client. We documented, analyzed and understood the requirements in detail, developed the test strategy, designed test scenarios, developed test scripts, provisioned test data, executed the tests, logged and managed defects. Great going. But there’s a twist to this smooth sailing story. The application interface and documentation was in French, not English.\n\nGood planning and rigorous documentation helped us not only meet delivery schedules, but also effectively communicate with all stakeholders. The planning and process rigor, which set in due to the initial ‘fear-of-language’ barrier, had worked wonders – enabling us to simplify complex system logic into meaningful, testable chunks of code. Strong reasoning and analytical skills allowed us to prioritize test execution. The language barrier in fact, pushed for an even more exhaustive exploratory testing – enabling the team to explore the system in far newer ways than usual, and discover defects, which otherwise would have made their way into production. The instance proves that good testing requires an exploratory mindset, supported by robust processes.\n \n![597f091686bcb.jpg](serve/attachment&path=597f091686bcb.jpg)  \n\n\nThis digital age, with its renewed focus on customer experience and robust IT frameworks, is the ideal time to be a QA and testing professional. Digital permeates all aspects of our personal and work lives – from smart software and wearables, to smart manufacturing and smart cities. These smart systems need extreme levels of reliability as economies and infrastructure depend on them. And behind the scenes, it’s QA that makes these IT systems smart, robust and secure.\n\nTo assure these digital deployments and smart IT systems end-to-end, there is a growing need for multi-skilled and talented testing workforce. Test engineers today don’t just test functionality in bits and pieces. They assure the business cycle. For example, in a grocery shopping mobile app, testers don’t just check order entry screens. They assure the end-to-end process – order entry into database, inventory updates, seamless back office integration, delivery notifications to the respective fulfillment partner (the local grocery store), and digital payments and checkouts. Imagine the sense of satisfaction testers feel, when they see these live systems making people’s lives easier.\n\nThe technical challenges in developing this elaborate ecosystem are immense. Developers and testers need to work in tandem to assure seamless functioning. For this, codes are checked into a code repository to check for build integrity and then tested automatically by scripts and deployed live. Major product companies boast of almost 23,000 deployments in a day; that is, around one production deployment every 11.6 seconds! The use of DevOps and Agile principles makes this possible. Quality assurance and testing practitioners with strong software testing skills are integral to assuring this ecosystem.\n\nIf you are ready to explore this exciting software testing journey, TESTimony is your chance. You can build core software testing skills, design robust tests, evaluate test design techniques, work with mobile testing tools, learn to manage software risks, and decide when software is good to go live! Arm yourself with tools to manage tests and defects, wield automation testing tools like never before, and push applications and networks beyond their performance abilities.','<p>We all agree quality assurance (QA) and testing is critical, and we have stories of moments which proved this right!