ibility, scalability, and frees the organization’s IT department to focus on high priority issues instead of things like phone maintenance.\n\n![597f16bcc4f35.jpg](serve/attachment&path=597f16bcc4f35.jpg)  \n\n \nHow cloud communication is different from other cloud-based services?\nCloud communication poses a completely unique set of demands on its providers. Unlike the majority of other cloud-based application services, which rely almost exclusively on internet connectivity, cloud communication is ultra-sensitive to network issues of packet loss, jitter and delay. This is because cloud communication involves the user’s real-time communication experiences. Consequently, IT architects and network planners should ensure that network architecture is optimized for service quality, and metrics are available at each IT service\n\nHow to deliver a quality cloud communication? T\nhe secret to delivering quality cloud communication lies in pursuing a tiered approach to managing Service-Level Agreements (SLA). An SLA reflects the user’s expectations of service and quality from a provider. SLAs may include penalties for nonperformance, but the objective must be to encourage a service provider to provide top-notch service, not pay penalties.\n\nHow does an SLA for each tier of service lead to quality cloud communication? Here’s how SLAs at each tier of service ensure quality in cloud communication:\nCommunications Application Tier: This tier includes the core communications application platform, along with infrastructure and connectivity. Within this tier, there are broadly three sub tiers of service - Telecom, Infrastructure, and Application. Service level for the communications application tier should encompass all of the sub tier components.\n\nTherefore, source a single SLA for all three sub tier components collectively, except where deviances cannot be avoided, such as when \nthere are commercial or technical limitations.\n\nWide-Area Network Tier: The WAN tier mostly involves multiple suppliers across both internal as well as web connections. The WAN provider should be expected to offer a service-level guarantee for transporting voice as well as video communications. The WAN tier should also include a service level for access to the internet in support of remote workers and customers. Internet access should be free from port blocking and meet minimum bandwidth and latency guarantees.\n\nLocal-Area Network Tier: Communications services traffic passes over a common LAN installed in each office location. Maintain an SLA with the communications as well as desktop maintenance service providers for this tier.\n\nDevice Tier: Connected devices include fixed phones, desktop PCs, laptops, conference bridges, tablets, smartphones, IoT devices, etc. All corporate supplied devices should have a clearly defined replacement policy in the event of failure. \n\nWith the above tiered approach, an enterprise can provide higher definition services with unmatched quality, and deliver a platform of advanced features that allow employees to work in ways – and places – they never imagined.','<p>Most businesses today are using some sort of cloud platform. Some studies indicate that &ldquo;by 2020, 80% of large enterprises will have migrated communications and collaboration infrastructure to cloud architecture, whether UCaaS, private or a hybrid cloud, up from 35% in 2016&rdquo;.</p>\n<p>Cloud communications is an entirely new way to build, deploy, and scale enterprise communications systems. It offers users with an array of sophisticated features such as edge traffic shaping, lower cost, flexibility, scalability, and frees the organization&rsquo;s IT department to focus on high priority issues instead of things like phone maintenance.</p>\n<p><img src=\"CODOF_RURI_58abe4df2c9c6_serve/attachment&amp;path=597f16bcc4f35.jpg\" alt=\"597f16bcc4f35.jpg\"></p>\n<p>How cloud communication is different from other cloud-based services?<br>Cloud communication poses 