 king. Any step required to allow your employees to do more with less, to work smarter not harder, and to be productive anytime and anyplace is a step you need to take.\n\nThis is a large part of the reason why workspaces are so popular these days – they let you do all this and more on your own terms. Before you make the move towards implementing a workspace in your own environment, however, there are a few key things you’ll want to keep in mind.\n\n![5981ba8cded56.jpg](serve/attachment&path=5981ba8cded56.jpg)  \n\n\nImplementing a Workspace: They’re No Longer a Recommendation\nThe most important thing you should know before implementing a workspace is that they are not some passing fad. They are not today’s “next big thing” that will be gone tomorrow. They are here to stay and they are the future of computing. The essential thing to do right now is to deploy them to an environment that is extremely reliable after partnering with a large company that has both been around and that will stay around.\n\nRemember that in this regard, bigger is better. You need to pick a service provider that you know isn’t going to fail – like AWS, Azure and more. When the stakes are this high, quality is more important than cost.\n\nIt’s Not an “All Or Nothing” Proposition\nThe second most important thing to understand about implementing a workspace is that you’re not talking about an “all or nothing” situation. You can deploy hybrid models if your current needs and future goals dictate that you should. It isn’t going to be a perfect fit for everyone, but not everyone is a perfect fit for the shape things have taken right now.\n\nConsider the cloud deployment of a medical practice to be just one example. An EHR system will likely be fine for day-to-day operations, but radiological images will likely be difficult to get into the platform as-is. These images will likely need to load at the time of creation to be used immediately, but this isn’t necessarily feasible right now. A hybrid model would do well in this type of situation.\n\nForget “Cookie Cutter”\nAnother key factor to keep in mind when implementing a workspace is that you’re not purchasing a product – you’re purchasing a service. As a result, you’re not looking for a “one size fits all” solution because there isn’t one – or at least, there shouldn’t be. You need to partner with someone who can understand your business first, design solutions second.\n\nThe Future Starts Now\nFinally, it’s essential for you to understand that when you’re talking about a shift as dramatic as workspaces, your workflow may change. There is going to be some level of architecture required. You may have to change your business processes or re-think what it means to be consistent. Time will prove, however, that this isn’t necessarily a bad thing.\n\nKey Takeaways:\n- Workspaces are the future of computing. Make no mistake about it, they are here to stay.\n- Workspaces are not an “all or nothing” proposition. You can (and likely should) deploy hybrid models.','<p>In the world of business technology, productivity is king. Any step required to allow your employees to do more with less, to work smarter not harder, and to be productive anytime and anyplace is a step you need to take.</p>\n<p>This is a large part of the reason why workspaces are so popular these days &ndash; they let you do all this and more on your own terms. Before you make the move towards implementing a workspace in your own environment, however, there are a few key things you&rsquo;ll want to keep in mind.</p>\n<p><img src=\"CODOF_RURI_58abe4df2c9c6_serve/attachment&amp;path=5981ba8cded56.jpg\" alt=\"5981ba8cded56.jpg\"></p>\n<p>Implementing a Workspace: They&rsquo;re No Longer a Recommendation<br>The most important thing you should know before implementing a workspace is that they are not some passing fad. They are not today&rsquo;s &ldquo;next big thing&rdquo; that will be gone tomorrow. They are here to stay and they are the future of computin