s other important tools needed to diagnose and treat patients accurately.\nThe ability to work from home or abroad – Workspaces allow medical personnel to access the tools they need from any location, which means that they can continue to work or consult with other medical personnel even when they are not on site.\n\nScalability – Healthcare workspaces can be scaled to meet the needs of any healthcare organization, whether it is a small clinic or a hospital with multiple locations.\nSecurity and convenience – Because workspaces are hosted and managed by a third-party provider, healthcare organizations don’t have to worry about updating software, maintaining hardware, providing security or dealing with any problems that may occur.\nObstacles to Adoption\nHealthcare workspaces are certain to become more popular in the future, but there are still some obstacles to adoption. For example, while cloud deployment of the EHR system works well, bringing radiological images to the cloud is much more difficult to accomplish. When radiological images are added to the workspace, the cost becomes unreasonably high.\n\nFortunately, it isn’t necessary to roll every aspect of the workspace out at once. Instead, healthcare organizations can move systems to the workplace one at a time as this technology continues to evolve.\n\nFor example, a healthcare organization may choose to use workspaces for patient records, test results and communications without attempting to add radiological images to the mix. Once it becomes more cost-effective to move radiological images into the workspaces, the organization can add them to the environment.\n\nKey Takeaways\n- Workspaces, which are digital environments delivered to users via the internet, will soon become the standard in the healthcare industry.\n- Healthcare workspaces offer many benefits to organizations in this industry, including scalability, convenience and security.\n- Not all systems and files are compatible with the workspace at this time. However, workspaces can be rolled out in phases and technology continues to evolve.','<p>Keeping records and sharing information is a key component of healthcare. In the past, these tasks were completed using paper and pen, as well as word-of-mouth. As time went on, newer technologies, such as electronic health record systems, became available to healthcare organizations. Soon, however, healthcare workspaces will be the new standard for organizations in this industry.</p>\n<p>What are Workspaces?<br>Workspaces are electronic environments that contain the files and software healthcare personnel need to do their jobs. These environments are delivered to personnel via the internet and can be accessed from any location with internet access. Instead of having loads of expensive hardware clogging up a medical practice or hospital environment, everything is connected to a server off-site.</p>\n<p><img src=\"CODOF_RURI_58abe4df2c9c6_serve/attachment&amp;path=5981bb3ba56d2.jpg\" alt=\"5981bb3ba56d2.jpg\"></p>\n<p>Benefits of Healthcare Workspaces<br>Workspaces offer several notable benefits to healthcare organizations. Some of these benefits include:</p>\n<p>Instant access to up-to-date information &ndash; When the workspace is designed properly, healthcare personnel are able to instantly access up-to-date test results, as well as other important tools needed to diagnose and treat patients accurately.<br>The ability to work from home or abroad &ndash; Workspaces allow medical personnel to access the tools they need from any location, which means that they can continue to work or consult with other medical personnel even when they are not on site.</p>\n<p>Scalability &ndash; Healthcare workspaces can be scaled to meet the needs of any healthcare organization, whether it is a small clinic or a hospital with multiple locations.<br>Security and convenience &ndash; Because workspaces are hosted and managed by a third-party provider, healthcare organizations don&rsquo;t ha